    <subsection>
        <title>Quotients and Exponents</title>
        <p>Working with quotients and exponents, a couple more rules come into play. Again, if we focus on the meaning of each exponent, we can figure out how these rules really work.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-quotient-of-powers-i">
            <title>The quotient of powers with the same base</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify <m>\frac{x^5}{x^2}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Without knowing a <q>rule</q> for simplifying this quotient of powers, we can write out products and simplify.<md>
                <mrow>\frac{x^5}{x^2} \amp= \frac{x \cdot x \cdot x \cdot x \cdot x}{x \cdot x}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= \frac{x}{x} \cdot \frac{x}{x} \cdot \frac{x \cdot x \cdot x}{1}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= 1 \cdot 1 \cdot x \cdot x \cdot x</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= x^3</mrow>
                </md>Notice that the difference of the exponents of the numerator and the denominator, <m>5</m> and <m>2</m> respectively, is <m>3</m>, the exponent of the simplified expression.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>This example generalizes to the <term>Quotient-of-Powers Rule</term>, for any nonzero real number <m>a</m>,<me>\dfrac{a^{n}}{a^{m}} = a^{n-m}.</me></p>

        <p>We can also apply an exponent to a quotient of different values.</p>

        <example>
            <title>The power of a quotient</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Let <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> be real numbers with <m>y \neq 0</m>. Simplify <m>\left( \frac{x}{y} \right)^3</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Writing out the product and simplifying gives<md>
                    <mrow>\left( \frac{x}{y} \right)^3 \amp= \left( \frac{x}{y} \right) \left( \frac{x}{y} \right) \left( \frac{x}{y} \right)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{x \cdot x \cdot x}{y \cdot y \cdot y}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{x^3}{y^3}</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>The previous example shows how the <term>Quotient-to-Power Rule</term> works. For real numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> with <m>b \neq 0</m>,<me>\left( \dfrac{a}{b}  \right)^{n} = \dfrac{a^{n}}{b^{n}}</me></p>
        
